0.header:
Dry mouth is unknown for some people, but to you it is killing you.

Food is difficult to swallow, seem dry, not as tasteful as you would expect because of a dry tongue.

And since saliva is in short supply, some enzymes that aid in digestion or even saliva that help to prevent tooth decay will be lacking.



It's okay. Let's see if there is anything over the counter to help with dry mouth.

But first, let's be sure you are looking at a dry mouth and not something more serious that will need urgent care or emergency room visit.

1.header:
Have you been diagnosed with dry mouth (xerostomia)?

Or this is your first time feeling your mouth being dry?

10.header:
Alright,
let's be sure you are looking at a dry mouth.

Lack of saliva which moistens the mouth and help with digestion will make your mouth feel dry.

11.header: Does it feel like your saliva is thick and stringy?

12.header:
Yes?
Dryness of the mouth can make it feel this way.

13.header: Does the tongue feel dry to you?

14.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of a dry mouth. The tongue feels dry.

15.header: Does food feel dry to you?

16.header:
Yes?
With a dry mouth food will feel dry. This is a symptom.

17.header: Are the corners of the mouth splitting?

18.header:
They are?
With dry mouth the corners of the mouth start splitting.

Dry mouth symptoms include:

  • Thick and Stringy saliva
  • Tongue feeling dry
  • Food feeling dry
  • Corners of mouth splitting

19.header: Are the lips cracking?

20.header:
Yes?
Absence of saliva to moisten the lips will make them crack.

Symptoms include:

  • Thick and Stringy saliva
  • Tongue feeling dry
  • Food feeling dry
  • Corners of mouth splitting
  • Cracking lips

21.header: Are you losing taste sensations?

22.header:
Yes?
This is a symptom of a dry mouth.

Symptoms include:

  • Thick and Stringy saliva
  • Tongue feeling dry
  • Food feeling dry
  • Corners of mouth splitting
  • Cracking lips
  • Loss of taste sensations

23.header: Are you having difficulty speaking?

24.header:
Yes?
With a dry mouth, you will have difficulty speaking.

25.header:
Do you think you have dry mouth because...

...food is hard to swallow?

27.header: Are you experiencing more tooth decaying?

28.header:
Yes?
Tooth decay usually accompany dryness of the mouth.

If you are also experiencing other symptoms described above, discuss this with your dentist or doctor.

29.header: Do you frequently experience soreness of the throat?

30.header:
You do?
Saliva not reaching the throat to moisturize it will make it sore.

31.header:
Those were the main symptoms of a dry mouth.

You should have a pretty good idea if you are looking at a dry mouth or not by now.

Let's continue and see what may be causing this.

40.header:
Are you currently taking prescription medications?

Most prescription medications can cause dry mouth.

41.header:
Yes?
Call the pharmacy and see if it has dry mouth as a side effect and then discuss this with your doctor.

Do not stop taking the medication without your doctor's knowledge.

42.header: With this dry mouth, do you also have fever?

43.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at something serious.

44.header: Do you have or had any diarrhea?

45.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • Sign of dehydration.

46.header: Did you start feeling dry mouth after excessive sweating?

47.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • May be looking at dehydration.

48.header:
There are other causes of dryness of the mouth.

The important thing is to make sure you are not looking at a dehydration situation.

If the dryness of the mouth is getting worse, you should discuss this with a doctor. It is very important to find out what is causing it. Bear in mind though that dry mouth is more common as you age and can be age related.

Let's see what a pharmacist recommend to help with this dry mouth that is available over-the-counter for now.

0.header:
An unpleasant odor that originates from the mouth and may cause personal embarrassment.

Up to half of the US population suffer from bad breath.



We can either mask it or try to find out what's causing it and get rid of it.

1.header: What would describe this breath odor?

buttonlist.title: Fruity or sweet chemical smell
Mousy or faintly sulfurous odor

2.header:
If fruity or sweet, it can be a sign of ketoacidosis.
This may occur in diabetics.

If you are diabetic, it means the body is trying to get rid of excess acetone through the breath.

This is life-threatening.
There is a lack of insulin. Which means the body cannot use your glucose as a source of fuel. So it is now using fat instead.

Ketone is the byproducts of fat breakdown and they are building up in your blood.

If you have missed a dose of insulin, go ahead and use it now. You need insulin. If not, then go to the nearest emergency room. This can be life threatening.

Would you like to visit the nearest urgent care or emergency room?

3.header:
May be looking at some kind of kidney failure here.

Chronic kidney failure can cause the breath to smell like ammonia. Some people would describe this as fishy or urine-like.

You should be seeing a doctor by now. Let the doctor know of the breath odor.

Would you like to visit the nearest urgent care or hospital?

4.header:
Looking at a possible bowel obstruction or severe constipation.

This can also happen if you have been vomiting for a long time, especially when there is bowel obstruction.

Try to take care of the constipation, get rid of the stomach gas or see if you can stop the vomiting.

If this continue, see the doctor. Would you like to visit the nearest urgent care or hospital, especially if this has been going on for a while now?

5.header:
Or faintly sulfurous?
Looking at a possible sign of liver failure

If under treatment of any kind, give the doctor a call as soon as possible or go to the nearest hospital for further evaluation.

10.header:
In addition to this breath odor, do you have fever?

Or a productive cough?

11.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • You may be looking at a serious infection of the respiratory pathways like the lungs or bronchioles.

12.header:
What about nasal discharge or headache?

Or facial pain?

13.header:
Seek urgent care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

  • You may be looking at a sinus infection here.

14.header: Do you also have a toothache with this bad breath?

15.header:
Seek dental care or call the doctor.

Here is why:

You may be looking at:

  • Abscessed tooth
  • Cavities
  • Gingivitis
  • Unerupted tooth

It is much better to take care of the underlying cause of the bad breath than to just mask it with mint or something else.

If you use dentures, ensure proper denture hygiene. Discuss this with the dentist to ensure proper use.

Would you like to see the nearest dentist to you or Continue?

16.header:
About 85% of bad breath is caused by poor oral conditions.

This is usually due to the growth of bacteria on the tongue, in-between the teeth and in cavities of the tooth.

You should see a dentist for a better analysis of your oral hygiene situation. To take care of bad breath, it is necessary to fix the underlying situation.

Until then let's see what is available over the counter to help with the bad breath.

Or would you like to see the nearest dentist to you?

22.title: Nasal Congestion
dlg:
Congestion is usually due to the inflammation and swelling of the blood vessels in the tissues that line the inside of the nose.

You will need a decongestant which helps to shrink the swollen blood vessels in the tissues or a steroidal nasal spray which helps with the inflammation helping to reduce the swelling.

3.header:
Nasal polyps?
Sac-like growths of inflamed tissue lining the nose or sinuses.

Symptoms usually include:

  • Runny nose
  • Reduced or complete loss of sense of smell
  • Nose feeling blocked
  • Breathing through the mouth

For nasal polyps, you would need to see a doctor. You will also need a steroidal nasal spray.

Well, let's see what a pharmacist can come up with until you see a doctor.

18.header: Have you used a decongestant nasal spray or drops for more than 3 days now?

19.header:
Yes?
Possibly looking at a rebound effect.

Using nasal spray decongestants for more than 3 days often lead to significant rebound congestion when the effects of the drug wear off, causing you to continue using the decongestant in a vicious circle of persistent, worsening congestion.

This situation called rhinitis medicamentosa may continue for some time and you may be thinking this is a continuation of the original problem rather than a side effect of using the nasal spray.

20.header:
See a doctor if the stuffiness is not accompanied by any other symptoms.

You may be looking at nasal polyps or a stuffy nose caused by medications like clonidine or flomax.

Also birth control pills and estrogen containing hormone replacement drugs may also cause nasal congestion in some women.

Let's see how bad it is.

23.title: Runny Nose
dlg: This excess mucus can also cause a cough that is worse at night and a sore throat may result from all the drainage to the back of the throat.

0.header:
Runny nose is excess mucus running outside the nose.

If the mucus run down the back of the throat, it is called postnasal drip.



Let's see if you can narrow down the cause before you see what a pharmacist recommend over the counter for the runny nose.

1.header: How would you describe the mucus being produced?

2.header:
Thin, clear, watery?
You may be looking at an allergy situation.

Bear in mind too that runny nose due to a cold most of the time start out clear and watery.

Let's continue to the allergy section to see what can be done. Or if you are thinking cold, let's visit the entry for cold.

3.header:
Thick, sticky, colored?
Alright, let's see if you need to see a doctor.

You may be looking at a sinus infection, inflammation, severe cold and flu or something else.

20.header:
Alright.
Assuming you are only looking at a runny nose.

When you have a runny nose, there is always a reason for it. It's more important to treat the source than the runny nose symptom itself.

It is also important to keep the mucus thin rather than thick and sticky. This helps prevent complications, such as ear and sinus infections, and plugging of your nasal passages.
